Electric Light Measurements.— Under this head we content ourselves with a warning. A bare statement that an electric arc light is of so many candle power really conveys no accurate information at alL The light from an electric arc differs greatly in colour from that of a candle;
Abney, Proc. Roy. Soc., 1878. a given arc light may have three thousand times as much red of a certain wave-length as a standard candle has of the same wave-length, but ten thousand times as much green light. Any one will admit that green light is not measurable in terms of red light; a mixture of red and green is not measurable in terms 0«. another mixture in which the proportions of the colours are wholly different. Again, the intensity of the light obtained from an arc light depends greatly on the direction in which it is viewed.
Allard, Mémoire sur les phares électriques, p. 13, Paris, 1881; Proc. Inst. C. E., Ivii. 130; Shoolbred, 59. Neither of these considerations applies in the same degree to incandescent lamps. (j. ho.)
